04276nam a22006615i 9780292798625DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212002txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927986257 a10.7560/7284242doi  a(DE-B1597)587293  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aLB1027.9b.G63 2002 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a379.1/11/09731 aGodwin, R. Kenneth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSchool Choice Tradeoffs :bLiberty, Equity, and Diversity /cR. Kenneth Godwin, Frank R. Kemerer. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (335 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. School Choice Options and Issues: An Overview -- t2. The Outcomes of School Choice Policies -- t3. Political Theory and School Choice -- t4. Parent Rights, School Choice, and Equality of Opportunity -- t5. Vouchers and Tax Benefits: Tradeoffs between Religious Freedom and Separation of Church and State -- t6. The Economics of Choice -- t7. School Choice Regulation: Accountability versus Autonomy -- t8. The Politics of Choice and a Proposed School Choice Policy -- tNotes -- tSelected References -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEducational policy in a democracy goes beyond teaching literacy and numeracy. It also supports teaching moral reasoning, political tolerance, respect for diversity, and citizenship. Education policy should encourage liberty and equality of opportunity, hold educational institutions accountable, and be efficient. School Choice Tradeoffs examines the tradeoffs among these goals when government affords parents the means to select the schools their children attend. Godwin and Kemerer compare current policy that uses family residence to assign students to schools with alternative policies that range from expanding public choice options to school vouchers. They identify the benefits and costs of each policy approach through a review of past empirical literature, the presentation of new empirical work, and legal and philosophic analysis. The authors offer a balanced perspective that goes beyond rhetoric and ideology to offer policymakers and the public insight into the complex tradeoffs that are inherent in the design and implementation of school choice policies. While all policies create winners and losers, the key questions concern who these individuals are and how much they gain or lose. By placing school choice within a broader context, this book will stimulate reflective thought in all readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEducation and statezUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aSchool choicezUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aKemerer, Frank R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKemerer, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuderman, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798625423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798625/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK